      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, I'm really glad you brought this up — two weeks of sharp knee pain is absolutely worth taking seriously, and it makes sense you're looking for answers.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: diagnosing what's going on with your knee is genuinely outside my lane as a running coach. Sharp pain that's lasted two weeks, especially with that stair-descending pattern, deserves proper eyes on it — a sports medicine doctor or physiotherapist can actually assess what's happening and give you a real answer. That's not me being overly cautious; it's just the right tool for the job.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question specifically — that's a medical decision, and I'd want you to run that by a doctor or pharmacist rather than your running coach. Taking anti-inflammatories before a run to mask pain is something I'd encourage you to get proper guidance on before doing.\n\n**What I can tell you from a coaching standpoint:** continuing to run through sharp, persistent pain — even shortened runs — risks turning something manageable into something that costs you a lot more time. I know that's not what you want to hear with your half marathon on the calendar, so let me offer some perspective on that.\n\n---\n\n**Here's the honest picture on your goal:**\n\nYou have until **July 11** — that's roughly 16 weeks out. Even if you needed 2–3 weeks of full rest and another 2–3 weeks of gradual return, you'd still have 10+ weeks of quality training to work with. That's a real runway. Your goal of 1:45:00 is achievable from where you are — but only if the foundation holds.\n\n---\n\n**What I'd suggest as a clear next step:** Get in to see a physiotherapist or sports medicine physician this week if you can. Once you have their guidance, come back to me and we'll build a plan that works within whatever parameters they give you.\n\nIn the meantime — what's your access to care like? Is seeing someone in the next few days realistic for you?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01DxDGWjLyhXUpfT5tj52EjD"
    }
